⭐ Commonly Used Data Science Models (The Real Core Set)
Across industries, a small set of models covers 80–90% of practical data science work.
These are the models you will repeatedly use in enterprise, startups, consulting, and product teams.

🔹 1. Linear Regression
Use for: Predicting continuous values (sales, revenue, demand)
Why it matters: Simple, interpretable, strong baseline

🔹 2. Logistic Regression
Use for: Binary classification (churn, fraud, conversion)
Why it matters: Fast, stable, interpretable, great baseline

🔹 3. Decision Trees
Use for: Rule‑based modeling, feature importance, interpretable logic
Why it matters: Human‑readable and easy to debug

🔹 4. Random Forest
Use for: Robust performance on tabular data with minimal tuning
Why it matters: Industry staple for credit risk, marketing, operations

🔹 5. Gradient Boosting (XGBoost / LightGBM / CatBoost)
Use for: High‑performance modeling on structured/tabular data
Why it matters: The workhorse of modern ML for business data

🔹 6. K‑Means (and other clustering)
Use for: Customer segmentation, product grouping, behavior clustering
Why it matters: Fast, intuitive, widely used in analytics

🔹 7. Time Series Models (ARIMA, Prophet, GBMs)
Use for: Forecasting demand, sales, traffic, inventory
Why it matters: Essential for planning and operations

🔹 8. Neural Networks (when needed)
Use for: Large, unstructured, or highly nonlinear data
Why it matters: Powerful but not the default for business tabular data

🧠 Summary Mental Model
The models you actually use repeatedly:
Linear Regression, Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, K‑Means, Time Series models

Everything else is niche or specialized.
